docs.abstract: Corey Lewandowski, the president’s former campaign manager, told stories about a Rolls-Royce and a platinum American Express card in explaining how the president understands regular people.
docs.snippet: Corey Lewandowski, the president’s former campaign manager, told stories about a Rolls-Royce and a platinum American Express card in explaining how the president understands regular people.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Being a billionaire president sometimes means confronting doubts that you understand the lives of regular people. That’s especially true for President Trump, who has built a political reputation for caring about working-class people despite decades of gold-plated living arrangements.

headline.main: Is Trump a Regular Guy? Yes, an Ex-Aide Says, Sometimes He Drives His Rolls-Royce
headline.print_headline: He Drives His Rolls-Royce Just Like Everybody Else

docs.abstract: The White House counsel, Donald F. McGahn II, was a witness to key episodes being scrutinized in the case. His cooperation with investigators is unusual.
docs.snippet: The White House counsel, Donald F. McGahn II, was a witness to key episodes being scrutinized in the case. His cooperation with investigators is unusual.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The White House counsel, Donald F. McGahn II, has cooperated extensively in the special counsel investigation, sharing detailed accounts about the episodes at the heart of the inquiry into whether President Trump obstructed justice, including some that investigators would not have learned of otherwise, according to a dozen current and former White House officials and others briefed on the matter.

headline.main: White House Counsel, Don McGahn, Has Cooperated Extensively in Mueller Inquiry
headline.print_headline: Top Trump Aide  Gives Mueller  Coveted Details

docs.abstract: The Supreme Court, which is short-handed as it awaits word of the fate of Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh’s nomination, seemed to be looking for a way to rule for the inmate without making a broad statement.
docs.snippet: The Supreme Court, which is short-handed as it awaits word of the fate of Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh’s nomination, seemed to be looking for a way to rule for the inmate without making a broad statement.
docs.lead_paragraph: In an unusually philosophical argument on the nature and consequences of human memory, the Supreme Court struggled on Tuesday to decide whether the Constitution allows Alabama to execute an inmate who cannot recall the 1985 murder that sent him to death row.

headline.main: Justices Weigh Case of Condemned Inmate Who Cannot Recall His Crime
headline.print_headline: Court Takes Up Case of Man Who Can’t Remember His Crime

docs.abstract: The drop has been particularly steep in parts of Europe and Latin America, according to a Pew Research Center survey. In only three countries have attitudes toward the U.S. improved since 2016.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The image of the United States around the world has fallen substantially since Donald J. Trump became president, according to a poll of foreigners in 25 countries that was released on Monday.

headline.main: Foreigners’ Views of America Dim Under Trump, Poll Shows
headline.print_headline: Poll Finds U.S. Popularity Nose-Dived Under Trump

docs.lead_paragraph: JOHNSON CITY, Tenn. — President Trump trained his sights on three leading Democratic prospects who could face him in his 2020 re-election battle, at a rally Monday evening that was ostensibly aimed at helping Tennessee Republicans facing a tough climate in the midterm elections.

headline.main: At a Rally Looking Toward November, Trump Sets His Sights Two Years Beyond

docs.abstract: In 1968, a top American military commander wanted to move nuclear weapons to South Vietnam to prevent defeat in a key battle. President Johnson refused.
docs.snippet: In 1968, a top American military commander wanted to move nuclear weapons to South Vietnam to prevent defeat in a key battle. President Johnson refused.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — In one of the darkest moments of the Vietnam War, the top American military commander in Saigon activated a plan in 1968 to move nuclear weapons to South Vietnam until he was overruled by President Lyndon B. Johnson, according to recently declassified documents cited in a new history of wartime presidential decisions.

headline.main: U.S. General Considered Nuclear Response in Vietnam War, Cables Show
headline.print_headline: U.S. Commander Moved to Place  Nuclear Arms in South Vietnam
